            {
              "id": "CVE-2025-8869",
              "name": "OsPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "CVE-2025-8869: Improper Link Resolution Before File Access ('Link Following')"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://scout.docker.com/v/CVE-2025-8869?s=github&n=pip&t=pypi&vr=%3C%3D25.2",
              "help": {
                "text": "When extracting a tar archive pip may not check symbolic links point into the extraction directory if the tarfile module doesn't implement PEP 706. Note that upgrading pip to a \"fixed\" version for this vulnerability doesn't fix all known vulnerabilities that are remediated by using a Python version that implements PEP 706. Note that this is a vulnerability in pip's fallback implementation of tar extraction for Python versions that don't implement PEP 706 and therefore are not secure to all vulnerabilities in the Python 'tarfile' module. If you're using a Python version that implements PEP 706 then pip doesn't use the \"vulnerable\" fallback code. Mitigations include upgrading to a version of pip that includes the fix, upgrading to a Python version that implements PEP 706 (Python >=3.9.17, >=3.10.12, >=3.11.4, or >=3.12), applying the linked patch, or inspecting source distributions (sdists) before installation as is already a best-practice.\n",
                "markdown": "> When extracting a tar archive pip may not check symbolic links point into the extraction directory if the tarfile module doesn't implement PEP 706. Note that upgrading pip to a \"fixed\" version for this vulnerability doesn't fix all known vulnerabilities that are remediated by using a Python version that implements PEP 706. Note that this is a vulnerability in pip's fallback implementation of tar extraction for Python versions that don't implement PEP 706 and therefore are not secure to all vulnerabilities in the Python 'tarfile' module. If you're using a Python version that implements PEP 706 then pip doesn't use the \"vulnerable\" fallback code. Mitigations include upgrading to a version of pip that includes the fix, upgrading to a Python version that implements PEP 706 (Python >=3.9.17, >=3.10.12, >=3.11.4, or >=3.12), applying the linked patch, or inspecting source distributions (sdists) before installation as is already a best-practice.\n\n|                                                                                                                       |\n|Package                                                                                           pkg:pypi/pip@23.0.1  |\n|Affected range                                                                                    <=25.2               |\n|Fixed version                                                                                     25.3                 |\n|[[CVSS Score 5.9] [CVSS Vector CVSS:4.0/AV:N/AC:L/AT:P/PR:N/UI:A/VC:N/VI:H/VA:N/SC:N/SI:N/SA:N]]                       |\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "affected_version": "<=25.2",
                "cvssV3": 5.9,
                "cvssV3_severity": "MEDIUM",
                "cvssV3_vector": "CVSS:4.0/AV:N/AC:L/AT:P/PR:N/UI:A/VC:N/VI:H/VA:N/SC:N/SI:N/SA:N",
                "fixed_version": "25.3",
                "purls": [
                  "pkg:pypi/pip@23.0.1"
                ],
                "security-severity": "5.9",
                "tags": [
                  "MEDIUM"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CVE-2023-5752",
              "name": "OsPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "CVE-2023-5752: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in a Command ('Command Injection')"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://scout.docker.com/v/CVE-2023-5752?s=github&n=pip&t=pypi&vr=%3C23.3",
              "help": {
                "text": "When installing a package from a Mercurial VCS URL, e.g. `pip install hg+...`, with pip prior to v23.3, the specified Mercurial revision could be used to inject arbitrary configuration options to the `hg clone` call (e.g. `--config`). Controlling the Mercurial configuration can modify how and which repository is installed. This vulnerability does not affect users who aren't installing from Mercurial.\n",
                "markdown": "> When installing a package from a Mercurial VCS URL, e.g. `pip install hg+...`, with pip prior to v23.3, the specified Mercurial revision could be used to inject arbitrary configuration options to the `hg clone` call (e.g. `--config`). Controlling the Mercurial configuration can modify how and which repository is installed. This vulnerability does not affect users who aren't installing from Mercurial.\n\n|                                                                                                                       |\n|Package                                                                                           pkg:pypi/pip@23.0.1  |\n|Affected range                                                                                    <23.3                |\n|Fixed version                                                                                     23.3                 |\n|[[CVSS Score 6.8] [CVSS Vector CVSS:4.0/AV:L/AC:L/AT:N/PR:L/UI:N/VC:N/VI:H/VA:N/SC:N/SI:N/SA:N]]                       |\n"
              },
              "properties": {
